Sea bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon are adorned with the motto: “The sea belongs to us by right.
It's our duty to get him back."
In all Bolivia, which has no access to the ocean, the memory of the lost outlet passed on to Chile after a bloody conflict in the 19th century, is still alive – as well as the call to sail again in the Pacific.
In fact, this hope is currently the strongest in decades, while Bolivia is awaiting judgment by the international court on October 1st, after five years have passed in consideration.
"The power is in Bolivia, there is a sense of serenity and unity everywhere, and the country expects a positive result," said Bolivian diplomat Roberto Kalzadila.
Many Bolivians will watch the judgment of the international court on the big screen across the country, hoping that the Hague tribunal will support Bolivia's claim and that after decades of negotiations, Chile will be obliged to give Bolivia sovereign access to the ocean.
Evo Morales, the charismatic local president of Bolivia, who is due to face a controversial re-election battle next year, has also bet a lot and a lot on the judgment of the court on Monday.
"We are very close to regaining access to the Pacific," Morales promised last August.
But some analysts believe that the possibility that the court will make a decision in favor of Bolivia is quite small, and even if it decides in its favor, that would not change things in reality.
The United Nations body in the Netherlands does not have the power to take over Chile's territory and has ruled that it will not determine the outcome of any negotiations.
The fact that the judgment of the international court is only six months after the hearing of the last arguments, points out that the case "is not complicated", recalls Paz Zarate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And instead of contributing to Bolivia's cause, the last four years may actually have hurt her.
"The problem of access to the ocean has been swelled by Bolivia's current government," Zarate said.
Then he hinted that Morales' warlike rhetoric had wiped out Chile's little remaining goodwill.
Bolivia and Chile will at some point continue the negotiations, but it will be extremely difficult after what has happened to have a normal dialogue.
The two countries have not maintained diplomatic missions with each other since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodriguez Veltze, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court's decision was taken unusually quickly.
According to him, on Monday Bolivia will have "an incredible opportunity to open the page of a new era in its relationship with Chile", as well as a chance to "end 139 years of disagreement by achieving benefits for both sides".
Kalzadila also rejected the idea that Morales -- who continues to be one of the most popular presidents in Latin America -- used the problem of ocean access as a "political crutch".
"Bolivia will never give up her right to go out to the Pacific," he added.
"Decision is an opportunity to see that we need to overcome our past problems."
