John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a reputation for academic distinction, which continues in 2018 with another superb performance of the exam results, which is only reinforced by individual and collective success in sports disciplines, art, music and other social sciences.
With up to 30,000 students all over Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Association of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to offer the best level to their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further education, their chosen career and their place in a global world.
As an educational sector that can draw up and implement a personal curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: “If you talk to someone in a language they understand, your words can reach them.
But if you speak his own language, you touch his heart."
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely only on the English language when we want to build relationships and trust with the peoples of other countries.
Through the results of this year's exams, we see that languages come first with the highest success for independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who have studied foreign languages have achieved the high A score.
The data collected from 74 members of SCIS schools shows that 72% of students have achieved a Chinese A rating, with 72% of students studying German, 69% of studied French and 63% of those with Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland perceive foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will definitely need in the future.
At the moment, languages as the subject of free choice by students receive the same attitude as natural-mathematic disciplines (scientific, technological, engineering and mathematical disciplines) both in the programmes of independent schools and beyond.
A study conducted in 2014 by the UK Commission on Employment and Employment Skills showed that, from the reasons employers have difficulty finding employees, 17% have indicated insufficient linguistic competence.
Therefore, more and more knowledge of foreign languages becomes mandatory in order to prepare young people for their future careers.
More and more jobs require the mastery of a foreign language, which makes these skills essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the chosen career, if a person masteres a foreign language, he will have a real advantage in the future after mastering such a skill that remains for life.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically puts the master of several languages ahead of the competition.
According to a study by YouGov, among more than 4,000 adult UK citizens in 2013, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to be able to conduct a language, with the French being the only language whose mastery reached a two-digit percentage with an indicator of 15%.
That is why investment in language learning today is important for children now.
Knowledge of several languages, especially those of developing economies, will provide children with a better chance of finding a good job.
In Scotland, each school will differ from taught languages.
A number of schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered more important to the UK in future by 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever interests your child has, there will always be enough languages to choose from in independent schools, and teachers will be specialists in their field.
Independent schools in Scotland are determined to provide an educational environment that will prepare children and give them the skills they need to succeed in life, regardless of what the future holds.
At the moment, it cannot be denied that in a global business environment, languages continue to play an incredibly important role in the future of any country, which requires this to be taken into account in the educational system.
Indeed, modern languages should be considered to be "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, along with diversity and excellent quality, to young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
