North Korea says "there is no way" to disarm unilaterally without trust
North Korean Foreign Minister told the UN on Saturday that continuing sanctions deepened distrust of the United States and there is no way the country would abandon its nuclear weapons unilaterally under such circumstances.
At the annual general meeting of the world organisation, Ri Young-ho said "significant measures of goodwill have been taken over the past year", for example, stopping nuclear and missile testing, destroying the nuclear test site and promising not to spread nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we do not see a corresponding reaction from the United States," he said.
"Without having confidence in the United States, we will not believe in our own national security and under no circumstances can we disarm ourselves first."
While Ri was expressing North Korea's known complaints about Washington's resistance against a "staged" approach to the elimination of nuclear weapons, in which North Korea would be rewarded because it had taken step-by-step measures, his statement seemed significant because it did not reject unilateral nuclear disarmament, as Pyongyang did in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement from Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between the President of the United States and the North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12th, when Kim promised to work for "nuclear disarmament on the Korean Peninsula", and Trump guaranteed North Korea's security.
North Korea has sought an official end to the 1950-1953 Korean War, but the United States says that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also opposed calls to ease the harsh international sanctions against North Korea.
"The US insists "first to remove nuclear weapons" and increase pressure through sanctions to achieve their goal through coercion, and even oppose "the declaration of the end of the war," Ri said.
"The perception that sanctions can make us fall to our knees is a meaningless dream of those who do not know us.
The problem, however, is that the continuing sanctions deepen our mistrust."
Ri did not mention whether a second meeting was planned between Kim and Trump, for which the US leader stressed through the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister focused on the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-In over the past five months and added: "If the country on the issue of nuclear disarmament were South Korea and not the United States, the elimination of nuclear weapons on the Korean peninsula would not have reached such a standstill.
However, Ri's tone of speech was significantly different from the previous year when he told the UN General Assembly that directing North Korean missiles to the mainland of the United States was inevitable after "the evil president" Trump called Kim "a man-missile" on a suicide mission.
This year, in the UN, Trump, who last year threatened North Korea with "total destruction", praised Kim for his courage to take disarmament measures, but said a lot of work remains to be done and sanctions must remain in place until North Korea eliminates nuclear weapons.
On Wednesday, Trump stressed that there is no deadline for this and said, "It doesn't matter whether it takes two years, three years or five months."
China and Russia say the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday that "The implementation of the Security Council sanctions must necessarily continue until full, final and confirmed nuclear disarmament is carried out."
The Security Council has unanimously strengthened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to stop financing Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programme.
Pompeo met with Ri at the UN General Assembly couloirs and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare a second summit.
This year Pompeo visited North Korea three times, but his last trip went well.
He left Pyongyang in July, saying progress was made, but just a few hours later North Korea accused him of making "gangster demands".
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea has promised to destroy a missile site and a nuclear complex if the United States takes "the appropriate measures".
According to him, Kim told him that "the appropriate measures" he seeks are the security guarantees Trump promised in Singapore and that he wants to achieve normalisation of relations with Washington.
Harvard students on a course for enough rest.
A new course at Harvard University this year caused all students to sleep more in an effort to fight the growing culture of learning "all night" with the help of caffeine.
A teacher found that students at number one university in the world often don't even think about it when it comes to the very foundations of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Keysler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham Hospital and Women's Hospital, has prepared a course he thinks is the first of his kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after talking about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end of the day, a girl came to me and said, "Why are they telling me this now, in my senior year?"
She said that no one ever talked to her about the importance of the dream that surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is held for the first time this year, explains to the students the most important thing about how good sleeping habits help academic and sports achievements, as well as improving general well-being.
Paul Bareira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of health services at the university, said the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that students were suffering from a serious lack of sleep during the week.
A one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one part there is an image of a room in a dorm where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers and books to explain to them the effects of caffeine and light, how sports achievements are influenced by lack of sleep, as well as the importance of bedtime routines.
Another part of the participants tells how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risks of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Then a map of the campus with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that this will not immediately change the behavior of students.
But we believe that they have the right to know – just as you have the right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke," Professor Kaisler added.
The culture of pride from "learning all night" still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and constantly increasing pressure on students means that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Providing adequate and quality sleep should be the "secret weapon" of students in the fight against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he says – even in order to avoid getting fat, as sleep deprivation puts the brain into starvation mode, which makes them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California who studied chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Keysler prepare a course by taking one of his classes in his first year at Harvard.
He says his course "opened his eyes" and inspired him to spread it throughout the campus.
He hopes that the next step is for all graduates to be asked to complete a similar curriculum before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Keysler recommends that students think about setting a bedtime and wake-up alarm and knowing the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can upset the circadian rhythm and lead to falling asleep problems.
