Most of the new cases are caused by sexual intercourse, which marks a change compared to the past.
Traditionally, HIV spreads rapidly to some parts of China as a result of a transfusion of infected blood.
However, the number of people infected with HIV in this way has been reduced to almost zero, China's health services said at a conference in Yunnan Province.
However, every year the number of those living with HIV and spin in China increases by 100,000.
The transmission of HIV through sexual contact is a serious problem in the LGBT community in China.
In 1997 homosexuality was decriminalized in China, but discrimination against people in KGB communities is widespread.
According to studies, because of conservative values, 70–90% of men who have had sexual relations with men end up marrying women.
Many of the cases of disease transmission are due to incorrect protection in these relationships.
In 2003, the Chinese government pledged to provide universal access to HIV drugs as part of efforts to address the problem.
