The National Trust follows the secret life of bats
A new study carried out in a mansion in the Scottish mountains aims to establish how bats use the landscape when hunting.
The hopes are that discoveries will shed new light on the behavior of unique flying mammals and help lead future conservation actions.
Research by scientists from the National Trust of Scotland will follow the common bats, as well as the brown Strelly Water Nightwear in Inverewe Gardens in Western Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed in key locations on the estate to track the activities of bats during the season.
Employees of NHS and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using manual detectors.
The expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the bat's call sounds, as well as which species produce them.
A map of the habitat and a report will then be drawn up to create a detailed landscape picture of their behavior.
Rob Duar, the NTS Nature Conservation Advisor, hopes the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important for bats and how they are used by any species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work, e.g. the creation of meadows, as well as the best way to maintain forest areas for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and in Britain as a whole declined significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction activities that affect their shelters and lead to habitat loss.
The risk to populations may be from wind turbines and lighting, aircraft and some chemical treatment of building materials, as well as attacks by pet cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, because of their hunting habits at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced echolocation techniques to detect insects and obstacles along their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historical buildings, 38 gardens of great importance and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
The Trust has trained experts who conduct regular studies, inspections of shelters and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization even created the first bat reserve in Scotland and the only special bat reserve in the Treave estate in the Dumfrees and Galloway area, which is home to eight of the ten bat species in Scotland.
The estate manager David Thompson says it's perfect territory for them.
"Here in Treave, we have great terrain for bats," he noted.
“We have old buildings, many old trees and completed a suitable habitat.
But there are many other things about bats that are not known, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us better understand what they need to thrive."
It emphasises that it is important to check for the presence of bats before carrying out property maintenance activities, as it is possible the unintentional destruction of an asylum to kill up to 400 female and young bats, as well as to destroy an entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass, disturb or destroy their shelters.
Elizabeth Farrell, a Scottish employee at the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said: “I still have a lot to learn about our bats and many of our animal species, because we just don’t know what’s happening to their populations.”
