Europe's team won the Ryder Cup for 2018, defeating the US team with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 of Le Golf National on the outskirts of Paris, France.
Thus, the United States has had six consecutive losses on European soil and has not won Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe regained the championship crown in the tournament after the team, led by Danish captain Thomas Bjorn, reached the required 14.5 points that guaranteed the victory of the United States.
The star of the United States, Phil Mikkelson, who performed poorly for most of the tournament, threw his first blow to the 16th hole (with a "par" 3) in the water, losing his match against Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari performed beautifully in all rounds, becoming one of the four players in the history of the tournament, reaching balance 5-0-0 since the race took place in the current format after 1979.
American Jordan Spite definitely lost 5 & 4 of the European team player at the lowest place in the ranking - Torbjorn Ole from Denmark.
The world leader Dustin Johnson lost 2 and 1 by Ian Poulter from England, for whom this is probably the last participation of Ryder Cup.
Spanish Sergio Garcia, a veteran with eight participations in Ryder Cup, became the European with the most points won in the tournament of all time, this year increasing his asset to 25.5 points.
“I usually don’t cry, but today I can’t help myself.
It's been a rough year.
I'm extremely grateful to Thomas for calling me and believing in me.
I'm so glad I can raise the bowl again.
All that matters is the team and I am happy to be able to help", said the excited Garcia after Europe's victory.
He passed the baton to his fellow countryman, John Ram, who defeated American legend Tiger Woods with 2 & 1 to the singles on Sunday.
"I am incredibly proud to have defeated Tiger Woods, yet I grew up watching him play," said 23-year-old Ram.
Woods has lost all four matches in France and his total balance of Ryder Cup is now 13-21-3.
Strange statistics about one of the greatest players of all time to win 14 major titles, an indicator that only gives way to Jack Niklaus.
The U.S. team was having a hard time all weekend except for Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who showed high-end golf every day of the tournament.
Team captain Jim Furrick said after the team’s disappointing performance: “I’m proud of these guys, they fought.
At some point this morning, we cornered Europe's team.
There was a fight.
I take my hat off to Thomas.
He's a great captain.
All 12 of his players did very well.
We will regroup, discuss important issues with the US Professional Golfers Association and our Ryder Cup Committee and look ahead.
I love these 12 boys, and I'm proud to be their captain.
You can't help but take off your opponent's hat.
We've just been outplayed."
New for the Red Tide: Concentrations decrease in Pinelas, Manothi and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Committee for Fish and Wild Animals shows a general reduction in concentrations of red tides in areas of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the Committee, there are reports of conditions for growth disruption in the regions of Pinelas, Manotti, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier – this shows a decrease in concentrations.
The waters with an excessive bloom of the red tide extend approximately 130 miles along the coast, from the northern Pinelas district to the southern Lee district.
Seaweed sections can be seen 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but they're less than last week.
The red tide is also observed in Pasco County.
In the past week, there has been reports of moderate concentrations in the coastal zone or slightly further inland in the county of Pinelas, low to high concentrations along the coast of Hilliborough County, conditions for high concentrations in the county of Manoe, conditions for high concentrations in the coastal area or further inland Sarasota, conditions for moderate concentrations in Charlotte County, conditions for high concentrations in the coast or further inland in Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
Reports continue to show respiratory tract inflammation in the districts of Pinelas, Manotti, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
Last week, there were no reports of respiratory tract inflammation in Northwestern Florida.
